            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="0"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_16525293' href='vote?id=16525293&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16523037'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=dahart" class="hnuser">dahart</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=16525293">12 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_16525293"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="4" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 16525293)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">&gt; or you use special pattern rules<p>I used make for years before I understood pattern rules, even though they&#x27;re pretty simple. I kept trying to use foreach loops all over the place. If you&#x27;re using foreach loops, check whether a pattern rule can do the job.<p>&gt; The popular clamour is that the autovars are too short &amp; confusing.<p>I finally realized, after years of using make and then learning pattern rules, that the three autovars listed here are visual mnemonics. $@ looks like a target, a ring with a bullseye. $&lt; is pointing left, so it&#x27;s the first prereq. $^ is like a horizontal bracket that groups all prereqs.<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=16525293&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16523037%2316525293">reply</a></u>
                  </font>
      </div></td></tr>
