        <tr class='athing comtr ' id='16524944'><td>
            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="80"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_16524944' href='vote?id=16524944&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16523037'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=rflrob" class="hnuser">rflrob</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=16524944">12 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_16524944"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="2" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 16524944)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">Yeah, -j just about does it, though with Snakemake you can also specify other resources (memory, I&#x2F;o, etc) for each task, and it will keep all of them under quota. So if you tell snakemake that task A takes six cores, but B-K take only one each, it will solve the knapsack problem to come up with some kind of optimal order for them, and on your 8-core machine you could have A, B, and C running, or B-K.<p>For a while, I muddled through with Make and a custom cluster job-submitter script, but the real Snakemake killer feature for me was multiple, independent wildcards. So I can, in one rule, have dir&#x2F;{databasename}&#x2F;{query}.tsv and rapidly hit multiple databases at once. If you are very clever (and rule one of Make is don’t be clever), you can have a GNUMake wildcard get parsed into multiple wildcards with the wimpy pattern substitution rules, but this is not a fun way to relax.<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=16524944&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16523037%2316524944">reply</a></u>
                  </font>
      </div></td></tr>
      </table></td></tr>
